Questions

Cases over Time

Grouping by date, compute the total number of new cases across all provinces. Create a plot with date on the x-axis and cases on the y-axis.

covid %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(cases = sum(cases)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, cases)) +
    geom_line()

Starting with the code you had above, add a scale_x_date that has breaks and minor breaks every 3 months. Label the date axis with “%Y %b”.

covid %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(cases = sum(cases)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, cases)) +
    geom_line() +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_minor_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = "%Y %b")

Modifying the code you had previously, add a rolling mean with roll_meanr over 14 days. Include two lines: one for the smoothed mean and the a line of the raw data with a “dotted” linetype a color of “grey75”.

covid %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(cases = sum(cases)) %>%
  mutate(cases_smooth = roll_meanr(cases, n = 14)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, cases)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = cases_smooth)) +
    geom_line(linetype = "dotted", color = "grey75") +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_minor_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = "%Y %b")

Notice that the data are very noisy when unsmoothed. Let’s see if this is a day of the week effect. Take the covid data, add a day of the week variable (use a label), group by the day of the week, and compute the average number of cases on each weekday. Take note of any patterns or differences.

covid %>%
  mutate(dow = wday(date, label = TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(dow) %>%
  summarize(cases = mean(cases))
## # A tibble: 7 × 2
##   dow   cases
##   <ord> <dbl>
## 1 Mon    50.5
## 2 Tue    62.6
## 3 Wed    73.5
## 4 Thu    81.4
## 5 Fri    82.9
## 6 Sat    78.7
## 7 Sun    69.8

Returning the last plot you made, create a rolling smoothing line over 7 days and another over 10 days. Plot both lines with different colors and observe which one is noisier. Usually we expect longer times to be smoother, but it will be the opposite here because of the day of the week effect.

covid %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(cases = sum(cases)) %>%
  mutate(cases_smooth_7 = roll_meanr(cases, n = 7)) %>%
  mutate(cases_smooth_10 = roll_meanr(cases, n = 10)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, cases)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = cases_smooth_7), color = "pink") +
    geom_line(aes(y = cases_smooth_10), alpha = 0.5) +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_minor_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = "%Y %b")

Italian Map

Next, take the province dataset and plot the regions. Transform the data set to the CRS code 7794 and fill the regions in the color white.

province %>%
  st_transform(7794) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(fill = "white")

Create a dataset called city_geo that is a spatial version of the city data. Arrange the dataset in ascenduing order of population (it will make the next plot look nicer).

city_geo <- city %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326, remove = FALSE) %>%
  arrange(pop)

Starting with the plot of provinces that you had above and add a layer of the cities on top. Have the size and color change with respect to the population of the city and use a scale_color_distiller to make a nice color scale.

province %>%
  st_transform(7794) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(fill = "white") +
    geom_sf(aes(size = pop, color = pop), data = city_geo) +
    scale_color_distiller(
      trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10
    )

Finally, create a data set called city_geo_lgl of the largest ten Italian cities. Below, add a geom_sf_label to the plot you created above with labels of the city names for these ten cities.

city_geo_lgl <- city_geo %>%
  arrange(desc(pop)) %>%
  slice(1:10)

province %>%
  st_transform(7794) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(fill = "white") +
    geom_sf(aes(size = pop, color = pop), data = city_geo) +
    geom_sf_label(aes(label = city_name), data = city_geo_lgl, nudge_y = 3e4) +
    scale_color_distiller(
      trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10
    )

Window Functions

Compute the floor of each date value in the covid dataset. Group by this weekly date and summarize the total number of cases across all of the provinces. Use the lag function to create a column called color that is “#cc241d” (red) when the number of cases increases over a week and “#458588” (green) when the number of cases decreases over a week. Create a plot with the data with date on the x-axis and the number of cases on the y-axis. Use a geom_segment layer showing that starts at the number of cases in the previous week and ends at the number of cases in the current week. Color the segments with the color variable you created and set the size to 1.

covid %>%
  mutate(date = floor_date(date, "week")) %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(cases = sum(cases)) %>%
  mutate(cases_lag = lag(cases)) %>%
  mutate(color = if_else(cases > cases_lag, "#cc241d", "#458588")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(date, cases)) +
    geom_segment(aes(xend = date, yend = cases_lag, color = color), size = 1) +
    scale_color_identity()

Below, again compute the number of cases each week. Filter the data to only include weeks that are local maxima: the number of cases was lower in the week before and after a given week.

covid %>%
  mutate(date = floor_date(date, "week")) %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarize(cases = sum(cases)) %>%
  mutate(cases_lead = lead(cases), cases_lag = lag(cases)) %>%
  filter(cases > cases_lead, cases > cases_lag)

Spatial Join

Using a spatial join, combine the city_geo with the province data. Compute the sum of the population of all cities in each province, convert the data to a tibble (use as_tibble, this removes the spatial metadata) and select just the province and pop columns. Save the result as a data set named prov_pop.

prov_pop <- city_geo %>%
  spatial_join(province) %>%
  group_by(province) %>%
  summarize(pop = sum(pop)) %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  select(province, pop)

prov_pop

Finally, use a left join to combine province and prov_pop. Create a spatial plot of the populations of the cities in each province using the fill aesthetic and a scale_fill_distiller scale.

province %>%
  left_join(prov_pop, by = "province") %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = pop), size = 0.2) +
    scale_fill_distiller(
      trans = "log2", palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10
    )
